ubi in mentem eius adventi venit, ‘ when a thought of his arrival has occurred to me.’ This construction of venire in mentem with a Genitive is not unfrequent in Cicero, e. g. Sull. 6. 19 cum matro- narum ac virginum veniebat z‘n mentem. The phrase is almost equiva- lent to meminisse in meaning and so takes the same construction. , It may be impersonal as here, or personal with the subject thought of in the nominative, as Liv. 8. 5 non venit z'n mentem pugna apud Regillum lacum. Cf. Madv. 5 291 , obs. 3. All MSS. give venit, except that the late con-ector of A has introduced an A, whence most editors read veniat. When ubi is used of indefinite frequency the Subjunctive naturally follows3 but in this oese Antipho may well be supposed to be thinking of the present occasion only.

adventi, archaic for adventas. In early Latin the Gen. of this declension ended in -uis, e. g. Heaut. 287 anuis. This was contracted (a) into -as‚ (b) into ἐπ’, the lightly pronounced s being first dropped, and then -ui shortened to -i. Only the form -as is employed by Augustan writers, but Ennius, Lucretius, Plautus, and Terence use both forms side by side. We find in Terence adventi, domi, fructi, ornati, quaesti, tumulti. N either Plautus nor Terence ever write domas.
